05398nam a22007695i 9783111317694DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831113176947 a10.1515/97831113176942doi  a(DE-B1597)654297  a(OCoLC)1409703119  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0042102bisacsh04a150.19521 aAlphandary, Idit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForgiveness and Resentment in the Aftermath of Mass Atrocity :bJewish Voices in Literature and Film /cIdit Alphandary. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (IX, 217 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on Jewish Texts and Contexts ,x2199-6962 ;v2400tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tList of figures -- tIntroduction Theorizing forgiveness and resentment in the presence of radical evil -- tChapter 1 Forgiveness, resentment and reconciliation – on W. G. Sebald -- tInterchapter 1 Aesthetic falsehood and emotion – on Bruno Schulz’s The Sanatorium Under the Hourglass and Wojciech Has’s The Hourglass Sanatorium -- tChapter 2 Love and worldliness – on Hannah Arendt -- tInterchapter 2 The necessary fragility of paradox – on Christian Petzold’s Phoenix -- tChapter 3 The sincerity of forgiveness – on Heinrich Böll and Jean Améry -- tInterchapter 3 Negative possessions – on Wladislaw Pasikowski’s Aftermath (Poklosie) -- tChapter 4 From emotion to national renewal – on J.M. Coetzee -- tInterchapter 4 Memory and nonviolence – on Raoul Peck’s I Am Not Your Negro -- tCoda Forgiveness, justice, and historical responsibility -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe author's starting point is the interweaving of forgiveness and resentment in the works of Jewish writers after the Holocaust, most especially Hannah Arendt and Jean Améry, to make sense of the catastrophe and to point to a way forward for both victims and perpetrators. The insights of these two writers and of several Jewish novelists and poets, including Bruno Schulz, Paul Celan, and Aharon Appelfeld, are used to develop accounts of forgiveness and resentment in other cases of mass atrocity around the world. The author offers a critical rereading of primary sources that aim to separate resentment from nonviolent resistance, and forgiveness from reconciliation. Forgiveness and resentment are not, as they might first appear, mutually exclusive. Together with Arendt, Améry, and Walter Benjamin, it is argued that it is through the interaction between them that victims of mass atrocity become agents of personal and cultural change. Together, forgiveness and resentment interrupt the present, reframe the past, and shape the future. They can reduce the chasm that separates memory and trust by fashioning new connections between identity and alterity, which can open paths to truly ethical coexistence for victims and perpetrators, and their descendants.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aApartheid.  aHannah Arendt.  aHolocaust.  aJean Améry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1z978311133219208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z9783111318820oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831113178160 cprintz